  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">pybbi, a Python software tool for reading genomic bigBed and bigWig files developed by Nezar Abdennur, has attracted early but high-quality scholarly attention since its 2024 release on Zenodo, with its sole recorded citation appearing in <em>Nature Cell Biology</em>.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Released in 2024 and archived on Zenodo as version 0.4.0, pybbi is a Python library designed to enable programmatic access to bigBed and bigWig binary indexed formats \u2014 compact, indexed file formats widely used in genomics to represent signal tracks and genomic interval annotations. The tool is maintained by Nezar Abdennur and its source code is publicly available on GitHub, reflecting an open development model appropriate for community-oriented scientific software.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The most telling signal of pybbi's impact is not the volume of its citations but their quality. Its single recorded citation to date comes from a 2025 article in <em>Nature Cell Biology</em>, a high-impact journal in cell and molecular biology. That study, examining how interphase chromosome conformation is specified through distinct folding programmes inherited via mitotic chromosomes or the cytoplasm, drew on contributions from researchers at institutions including the University of Massachusetts Chan Medical School, MIT, Howard Hughes Medical Institute, and the National Institute of Child Health. The fact that a tool-focused deposit attracted uptake in this context \u2014 by a prominent chromosome biology group centered around J. Dekker's lab \u2014 suggests pybbi is serving as practical infrastructure for genome-scale data analysis pipelines in chromatin research.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The citing work itself carries a median citation count of 9, indicating it is already gaining traction within the community it serves. This downstream reach, though mediated through a single publication at present, places pybbi in a lineage of computational utilities whose value is realized not through direct scholarly debate but through quiet, essential incorporation into data analysis workflows. The software's relevance to genomics is consistent with the broader ecosystem of tools supporting chromatin conformation capture (Hi-C) and epigenomic signal visualization.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">As a recently deposited software record, pybbi's Zenodo presence provides a citable, versioned archive that supports reproducibility in computational biology. While formal attention metrics such as views and downloads are not yet reflected in the DataCite record, the tool's GitHub-linked release and its uptake in peer-reviewed research indicate an active user base operating outside the formal citation system. For a specialized bioinformatics utility, early adoption by high-visibility research groups is a meaningful indicator of utility and trustworthiness within its domain.</p>",
